<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06237010 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06237010 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  US; GOVERNMENT; ESPIONAGE; RELIGION; REGULATION  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  UNDERCOVER government spies cannot infiltrate worship services, Bible studyclasses or church meetings under a court ruling that now stands as a landmarkprecedent.;   &quot;It's the first established decision in the history of thecountry that curbs the government from going into churches in a clandestineway and spying on them,&quot; said attorney Peter Baird of Phoenix, who pressed thecase.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Religion andamp; Ethics  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  NO SPIES ALLOWED IN CHURCH  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Courts  </MEMO><TEXT>     The decision, won in a lawsuit by four Presbyterian and Lutherancongregations in Arizona and their national denominations, became a solidprecedent last week when the U.S. Justice Department decided not to appealit.;   The current case dates to the &quot;sanctuary movement&quot; in the mid-1980swhen various churches around the country provided sanctuary to refugees fromwar-ridden El Salvador.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910824  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  123  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday, August 24, 199100237010,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>